    "author_association": "MEMBER",
    "body": "# Problem\r\n\r\nWriting test code requires some \"tribal knowledge\" that requires the test author to understand which \"helper\" functions are dispatched to the `nvim` _test session_ (the \"[SUT](https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/System_under_test)\") and which functions are handled in the context of the _test runner_.\r\n\r\nContributors must constantly be aware of the difference. Reading and writing tests can be confusing because of this, especially to non-experienced contributors.\r\n\r\n# Expected behavior\r\n\r\nMake the distinction clear by either extracting SUT functions to `test/sut.lua` or grouping them in a ~~sut~~ `nvim` container.\r\n\r\n- [x] Rename `helpers.lua` to `testutil.lua` and change the import convention to (https://github.com/neovim/neovim/pull/28145):\r\n   ```\r\n   local t = require('testutil')\r\n   ...\r\n   t.foo()\r\n   t.bar()\r\n   ```\r\n    - Thus there is no need anymore to do this:\r\n      ```\r\n      local helpers = require('testutil')\r\n      local foo = helpers.foo\r\n      local bar = helpers.bar\r\n      ```\r\n    - Test code can simply use `t.xx()` everywhere to call non-SUT test util functions.\r\n- [ ] SUT functions live on `nvim`. When using SUT functions in test code, the usage looks like:\r\n   ```lua\r\n   nvim.api.nvim_get_commands()  -- instead of helpers.api.nvim_get_commands\r\n   nvim.fn.foo()  -- instead of helpers.fn.foo()\r\n   ```\r\n    - See \"Implementation\" below.\r\n\r\n# Implementation\r\n\r\nAlmost everything in `test/functional/testutil.lua` involves a \"session\". So in practice this would mean:\r\n\r\n1. Lift any \"pure\" functionality (functions that don't require the nvim \"test session\") from `test/functional/testutil.lua` into `test/testutil.lua`.\r\n    - `test/functional/testutil.lua` calls the `nvim` \"test session\" via RPC.\r\n1. `test/testutil.lua` is no longer \"merged\" into `test/functional/testutil.lua`.\r\n    - I.e. delete this line: https://github.com/neovim/neovim/blob/fd085d90820149caecf213b299f19e46305043ee/test/functional/testutil.lua#L19\r\n1. Rename `test/functional/testutil.lua` to (e.g.) `…/nvimsession.lua`\r\n1. All test imports now look like:\r\n   ```lua\r\n   -- Test runner functions/utils.\r\n   local t = require('test.testutil')()\r\n   -- Nvim RPC session.\r\n   local nvim = require('test.functional.nvimsession')()\r\n   ```\r\n    - What should the test session be named?\r\n        - ~~nvim? session? sut?~~ We decided on `n`.\r\n\r\n# Future\r\n\r\nSome questions to consider for the future (out of scope for this issue):\r\n\r\n- Should `nvim` be a mirror of the nvim \"test session\" Lua stdlib? I.e. all `nvim.xx()` calls just dispatch to the Nvim \"test session\" `vim.xx()` ?\r\n- Currently, we have a global \"session\": https://github.com/neovim/neovim/blob/f190f758ac58d9cc955368e047b070e0a2261033/test/functional/testutil.lua#L107-L113\r\n    - This makes it less obvious what's going on in the tests.\r\n    - It is weird that \"screen\" is used as an object in test code while \"session\" is not. Especially since the \"screen\" object is strictly tied to a session anyway. You cannot have multiple screens per session.\r\n    - Solution: we could treat the Nvim session same as \"screen\", so tests would look like:\r\n      ```\r\n      local nvim = require('…/nvimsession.lua')\r\n      local n = nvim.clear()\r\n      n:command(':new foo')\r\n      t.eq(2, n:eval('1+1'))\r\n      ```\r\n\r\n# Related\r\n\r\n- https://github.com/neovim/neovim/pull/26994\r\n- https://github.com/neovim/neovim/pull/27024",
